  "prompt": "What are the best anime movies?",
  "response": "The \"best\" anime movies can be subjective and depend on personal tastes, but there are several that are widely acclaimed by critics and audiences alike. Here are some of the most highly regarded anime films:\n\n1. **Studio Ghibli Films**:\n   - *Spirited Away* (2001) - Directed by Hayao Miyazaki, this film won the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature and is often considered one of the greatest animated films of all time.\n   - *My Neighbor Totoro* (1988) - Another Miyazaki classic that has become an iconic piece of family-friendly animation.\n   - *Princess Mononoke* (1997) - A more adult-oriented film that explores the themes of environmentalism and industrialization.\n   - *Grave of the Fireflies* (1988) - A powerful anti-war film directed by Isao Takahata.\n\n2. **Mamoru Hosoda Films**:\n   - *Wolf Children* (2012) - A story about motherhood and the struggles of raising children who are different.\n   - *The Girl Who Leapt Through Time* (2006) - A science fiction romance that explores the consequences of time travel.\n   - *Mirai* (2018) - A heartwarming tale of a young boy who encounters his family members from different points in time.\n\n3. **Makoto Shinkai Films**:\n   - *Your Name* (2016) - A body-swapping romance that became a global phenomenon.\n   - *Weathering With You* (2019) - A story about a boy who has the power to manipulate the weather.\n\n4. **Satoshi Kon Films**:\n   - *Perfect Blue* (1997) - A psychological thriller that delves into the pressures of celebrity and identity.\n   - *Paprika* (2006) - A surreal exploration of dreams and technology.\n\n5. **Katsuhiro Otomo Films**:\n   - *Akira* (1988) - A landmark cyberpunk film that has had a significant influence on science fiction animation.\n\n6. **Masaaki Yuasa Films**:\n   - *Mind Game* (2004) - A wild and unconventional film that combines various animation styles and storytelling techniques.\n   - *Ride Your Wave* (2019) - A love story that deals with loss and moving on.\n\n7. **Other Notable Films**:\n   - *The Tale of the Princess Kaguya* (2013) - A beautifully animated film from Studio Ghibli that retells a classic Japanese folktale.\n   - *A Silent Voice* (2016) - A poignant story about bullying, redemption, and the power of understanding.\n   - *Ghost in the Shell* (1995) - A cyberpunk masterpiece that explores themes of identity in a technologically advanced future.\n\nThese films are just the tip of the iceberg when it comes to the rich and diverse world of anime movies. Each brings its own unique storytelling, artistic style, and thematic depth to the medium.",
